question:
Let R be a ring and let U and V be (two-sided) ideals of R. Which of the following must also be ideals of R ?
I. {u + v : u \in and v \in V}
II. {uv : u \in U and v \in V}
III. {x : x \in U and x \in V}

r_prime:
Okay, let’s see. The problem is asking for the total number of palindromes of length ≥ 2, built from any subset of the letters in MISSISSIPPI, that contain at least one M.  

Since there is only one M available, M must sit in the center of every allowable palindrome; the rest of the word is determined entirely by the multiset that appears to the left of that central M.  The stock of other letters is I⁴, S⁴, P², so every letter used outside the middle has to occur an even number of times—half of each pair on the left, half on the right.

List the feasible even counts (i, s, p):  
(2,0,0), (0,2,0), (0,0,2);  
(2,2,0), (2,0,2), (0,2,2), (4,0,0), (0,4,0);  
(4,2,0), (4,0,2), (2,4,0), (0,4,2), (2,2,2);  
(4,4,0), (4,2,2), (2,4,2);  
(4,4,2).

For each choice, let L=(i+s+p)/2 be the length of the half–string.  The number of distinct left halves is  

 L! / [(i/2)! (s/2)! (p/2)!].

The only time this over-counts is when all three letters appear once each—i.e. the half “ISP.”  Because ISP and its reverse PSI lead to the same full palindrome, we divide that particular 6 by 2, counting only 3 instead.  Summing the individual contributions 3, 5, 13, 15, 15, and 35 gives the grand total.
